revision.text:
Over eight thousand years of history make up the background of ''[[The Second Apocalypse]].''

==Dating==
Without a [[Nonman]] standardized dating system (they find humanity's desire for such accuracy to be baffling), there is no way to reconstruct the exact chronology of the First Age. However, according to [[R. Scott Bakker]], the maximum lifespan of the [[Nonmen]] before the [[Womb Plague]] was approximately 400 years. [[Cû’jara-Cinmoi]] was in his prime when the [[Incû-Holoinas]] fell from the skies and was near death when the Womb Plague took place, suggesting these events spanned 200-300 years. The Womb Plague marked the beginning of the [[Cûno-Inchoroi Wars]], which are said to have lasted five centuries. The [[Breaking of the Gates]] and the invasion of men then began an unknown period after that. This suggests the events of the First Age, as recounted, may have lasted for around one thousand years and potentially significantly longer.

Two important clues are given to the dating of events: the claim that the [[Heron Spear]] spent "thousands of years" in [[Ishoriöl]] (so at least 2,000 years passed between the Heron Spear being installed there and its theft circa 750 Year-of-the-Tusk)<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Heron Spear'</ref>; and the suggestion by [[Cet’ingira]] in 4132 that he had lived for 8,000 years (placing the Inoculation in a 400-year span around that point, depending on his age upon receiving it, and Arkfall a century to three centuries before that). The latter claim may be debatable, due to the Erratic's own issues with memory and madness.<ref>''[[The Unholy Consult]]''</ref>.

The Breaking of the Gates marks the beginning of the calendar of the [[The Chronicle of the Tusk|Tusk]], which all subsequent events are dated from.

==The First Age==
The First Age began with the founding of Nonman civilisation by [[Imimorûl]] and concluded with the Breaking of the Gates, from which time human civilisation in [[Eärwa]] is dated. This period of time is chronicled in the Nonman historical and spiritual text, the ''[[Isûphiryas]]'', but human chroniclers find it difficult to read the volume due to its chronicling of events in reverse order (so, from newest to oldest) since the Nonmen believe that to understand events you have to first know the consequence. There is also no methodology of dating events in the work, either reliably to one another or to later events.

The central and most important sequence of events in the First Age are the [[Cûno-Inchoroi Wars]], which began (arguably) with the [[Arkfall]], were suspended during the [[Inoculation]], began again with the [[Womb Plague]] and concluded with the [[Battle of Isal’imial]] and the cleansing of the Ark five centuries later.

==Approximate sequence of events in the First Age==
* '''[[Nonmen]] Prehistory''': [[Imimorûl]] is banished from the heavens and founds Nonman civilisation. Siöl and Nihrimsul are founded. Imimorûl dies, [[Tsonos]] succeeds him. Siöl founds [[Ishoriöl]], Viri, [[Cil-Aujas]] and [[Illisserû]]; they in turn found [[Curunq]], [[Cil-Aumûl]] and [[Incissal]].
* '''[[Thousand Year Siege]]''': Siöl and Nihrimsul fight many skirmishes, most notably the [[Thousand Year Siege]], before an uneasy peace develops.
* '''[[Arkfall]]''': The [[Incû-Holoinas]] crashes in western Viri, devastating the Mansion's domains. Siöl invades and conquers Viri, Nihrimsul and Cil-Aujas in short order. First contact is made with the [[Inchoroi]]. The [[First Watch]] is placed about the Ark.
* '''[[Battle of Pir Pahal]]''': The Inchoroi ally with Nin’janjin, the Traitor-King of Viri. They breach the First Watch in the First Battle of the Ark. [[Cû’jara-Cinmoi]] rallies the Four Mansions and defeats the Inchoroi on the field of Pir Pahal, slaying [[Sil]], King of the Inchoroi and seizing the [[Heron Spear]]. The Inchoroi and Nin'janjin retreat to the Ark. Nihrimsul and Cil-Aujas rebel against Cû’jara-Cinmoi. The [[Second Watch]] begins.
* '''Siöl-Nihrimsul Wars''': The two Mansions fight a long (100-200 year) campaign, with Siöl eventually recapturing Cil-Aujas. Nihrimsul refuses to surrender again, however. [[Sin’niroiha]] is gifted the [[False Sun|Day Lantern]] by [[Emilidis]] and uses this to establish an alliance with Ishoriöl. Wary of Ishoriöl's strength, Cû’jara-Cinmoi sues for peace.
* '''The [[Inoculation]]''': Nin'janjin, acting as an emissary for the Inchoroi, sues for peace with the ageing and failing Cû’jara-Cinmoi. Cû’jara-Cinmoi agrees on the condition that the Inchoroi share the secret of immortality with the Nonmen. The Second Watch is disbanded and the Inchoroi begin administering to the Nonmen.
* '''The [[Womb Plague]]''': Over 100 years after the Inoculation begins, all Nonmen women die as a result of the Inchoroi plotting. Cû’jara-Cinmoi declares vengeance and summons the might of all the High Mansions to war.
* '''[[Battle of Pir Minginnial]]''': Second Battle of the Ark. Cû’jara-Cinmoi is slain on the field of [[Inniür-Shigogli]] by the treachery of Nin'janjin. [[Chorae]], [[Sranc]], [[Bashrag|Bashrags]] and [[Wracu]] appear for the first time. Sin’niroiha rallies the Nonmen and withdraws from the field.
* '''[[Cûno-Inchoroi Wars]]''': Lasting 500 years after Pir Minginnial (some hold that the wars began with Arkfall, others with the Womb Plague and Pir Minginnial).
** '''Sieges of Ishoriöl''': The Exalted Mansion spends over 50 years under siege in five separate campaigns. Sin’niroiha becomes the last Nonman to die of old age and is succeeded by his son, [[Nil’giccas]].
** '''[[Battle of Imogirion]]''': The Mansion of [[Illisserû]] mounts a seaborne assault on the Inchoroi, landing an invasion force on the [[Leash]] and marching on the Ark. They are defeated with great loss of life. Only one of the invaders lives to see home again.
** '''Second Summoning''': Nil'giccas unites the High Mansions a second time and assembles a host mighty enough to challenge the Inchoroi.
** '''[[Battle of Isal’imial]]''': Nil'giccas and his host smash the Inchoroi armies in the shadow of the Ark, driving the Sranc into the [[Yimaleti Mountains]], allegedly completely destroying the Inchoroi and breaching the Ark.
** '''Cleansing of the Ark''': The Nonmen spend twenty years looting and desecrating the Ark, but are unable to destroy it. Troubled by the [[Golden Room]] and the [[Inverse Fire]] it holds, and outright disturbed by the testimony of the captive Nin'janjin and [[Cet’ingira]], Nil'giccas has the [[Barricades]] raised around the Ark and then evacuate it, forbidding any from coming close.
* Centuries after the Cleansing, the two surviving Inchoroi create the Tusk and gift it to the men of [[Eänna]]. The Tusk is an accurate collection of their scriptures with only one insertion: the religious command to invade Eärwa and kill the Nonmen.

==The Second Age==
===Far Antiquity ''(0-2155)''===
* '''0'''—The legendary [[Gates of Eärwa|Breaking of the Gates]],{{EG|Year-of-the-Tusk}} the name given to the assault on the Gates of Eärwa, a series of fortified passes through the [[Great Kayarsus]], by the Men of [[Eänna]].{{EG|Breaking of the Gates}} [[Angeshraël]], the most famed Old Prophet of the Tusk, leads the [[Five Tribes of Men]]: the [[Norsirai]], the [[Ketyai]], the [[Satyothi]], the [[Scylvendi]], and the [[Xiuhianni]] into Eärwa,{{EG|Angeshraël}} though according to ''The Chronicle of the Tusk,'' the Xiuhianni refused to follow the other four tribes.{{EG|Xiuhianni}} This marks the beginning of the Second Age.{{EG|Five Tribes of Men}} It is also the beginning of [[Far Antiquity]],{{EG|Far Antiquity}} or the Age of Bronze when bronze was the dominant technology of Men.{{EG|Age of Bronze}} Since ''The Chronicle of the Tusk'' ends with the determination to invade Eärwa, or the Land of the “Uplifted Sun,” and since the Nonman Mansions most involved in resisting the Tribes of Men were all destroyed, very little is known either of the Breaking of the Gates or of the subsequent migratory invasions.{{EG|Breaking of the Gates}}
* '''?'''—The Prophet Angeshraël incites the Four Nations of Men to embark on a holy war of extermination the Nonmen.{{EG|Nonmen}} Nonmen and Men fight the [[Cûno-Halaroi Wars]], of which very few accounts exist.{{EG|Cûno-Halaroi Wars}} Within the course of a few generations Nonmen were nearly exterminated. Only the Mansions of Ishoriöl and Cil-Aujas survived.{{EG|Nonmen}}
* '''?'''—The [[Jiünati Steppe]] is inhabited by Scylvendi pastoralists.{{EG|Jiünati Steppe}}
* '''?'''—Over a relatively brief period of time, the High Norsirai tribes that settled the rich alluvial plains along the lower [[River Aumris]] founded the first cities of Men, including [[Trysë]], [[Sauglish]], [[Etrith|Etrithatta]] (often called Etrith), and [[Ûmerau]]. As the result of trade with the Nonmen of [[Injor-Niyas]], the power and sophistication of the Aumris River civilization grows quickly.{{EG|Aumris River}}
* '''''c.'' 300 / 4th c.'''—High Norsirai city-states along the River Aumris unite under [[Cûnwerishau]], the God-King of Trysë.{{EG|Aumris River}}{{EG|Kûniüri}} Sometime in the fourth century, Cûnwerishau and Nil’giccas, the Nonman King of Ishoriöl ([[Ishterebinth]]), make a treaty between their two peoples, the first between Nonmen and Men. As part of the treaty, Cûnwerishau is given a copy of the ''Isûphiryas,'' the great work chronicling the history of the Nonmen prior to the Breaking of the Gates.{{EG|''Isûphiryas''}}
* '''''c.'' 430'''—God-Kings of Trysë are overthrown. The [[Ûmeri Empire]], the first great nation of Men, encompassing the length of the River Aumris, is founded.{{EG|Umeri Empire}}
* '''''c.'' 500'''—The city of Ûmerau gains ascendancy, leading to the Ûmerau Empire and the cultural efflorescence of the [[Nonman Tutelage]] under [[Carû-Ongonean]].{{EG|Kûniüri}} A number of [[Hamori]] Ketyai tribes settle the length of the [[River Sayut]] and the [[Secharib Plains]], becoming more sedentary and socially stratified as they exploit the rich cereal yields afforded by the fertile soils of the region. [[Seto-Annaria]], as it came to be called (after the two most dominant tribes), remains a collection of warring city-states.{{EG|Shiradi Empire}}
* '''''c.'' 549'''—[[Nincaerû-Telesser]], fourth God-King of the Ûmeri Empire, and famed patron of the ancient [[Gnosis|Gnostic]] [[The Schools|Schools]], is born.{{EG|Nincaerû-Telesser}} The beginning of his reign is unknown. The 3rd Ûmeri God-King is still reigning in 570, when Nincaerû-Telesser would have been 21.
* '''555'''—Beginning of the Nonman Tutelage, the great period of Norsirai-Cûnuroi trade, education, and strategic alliances.{{EG|Nonmen Tutelage}} The Nonmen who served men at this time were called [[Siqû]].{{EG|Siqu}} The Gnosis, first developed by the Nonmen Qûya, is imparted to the early Norsirai [[Anagogis|Anagogic]] sorcerers.{{EG|Gnosis}} First references to [[benjuka]] are from this period.{{EG|benjuka}}
* '''''c.'' 560'''—Great [[Library of Sauglish]], is founded by Carû-Ongonean, the third Ûmeri God-King.{{EG|Great Library of Sauglish}} During the reign of the Carû-Ongonean, five Ûmeri translations of the ''Isûphiryas'' were bequeathed to the Library of Sauglish.{{EG|''Isûphiryas''}}
* '''''c.'' 570'''—The fortress of Ara-Etrith (“New Etrith”), latter called [[Atrithau]], is founded by Carû-Ongonean, third Ûmeri God-King.{{EG|Atrithau}}
* '''574'''—[[Nincaerû-Telesser II]], who will transform Great Library of Sauglish into the cultural heart of the [[Ancient North]], is born.{{EG|Great Library of Sauglish}}<ref group="Notes">Nincaerû-Telesser II is likely the 5th King. If so he is enthroned in ''c.'' 642 at age 68.</ref>
* '''622'''—[[Palpothis III]], Old Dynasty God-King of [[Shigek]] is born. He will raise the [[Palpothis|Ziggurat]] that bears his name.{{EG|Palpothis}}
* '''''c.'' 642'''—Nincaerû-Telesser, fourth God-King Ûmeri, dies at age 93.{{EG|Nincaerû-Telesser}}
* '''668'''—Nincaerû-Telesser II, dies at age 94.{{EG|Great Library of Sauglish}} During his reign (574-668) the Nonman Siqû [[Gin’yursis]] founds the Gnostic School of [[Sohonc]].
* '''''c.'' 670'''—[[Xijoser]], the Old Dynasty God-King of Shigek, who will raise the largest of the [[Ziggurats of Shigek]], is born.{{EG|Great Ziggurat of Xijoser}}{{EG|Xijoser}}
* '''678'''—Palpothis III, the Old Dynasty God-King of Shigek, dies at age 56.{{EG|Palpothis}}
* '''684'''—The Gnostic School of [[Mangaecca]] is founded by [[Sos-Praniura]] (the greatest student of Gin’yursis).{{EG|Mangaecca}}
* '''''c.'' 687'''—[[Gotagga]], the great Ûmeri sorcerer credited with the birth of philosophy apart from theological speculation, is born.{{EG|Gotagga}}
* '''''c.'' 720'''—Xijoser, the Old Dynasty God-King of Shigek, dies at age 50.{{EG|Xijoser}}
* '''735'''—Gotagga, the great Ûmeri sorcerer, dies at age 48.{{EG|Gotagga}}
* '''''c.'' 750'''—The Heron Spear, or Suörgil (“Shining Death” in Ihrimsû), is stolen by [[Cet’ingira]], or Mekeritrig, from the Nonmen of Ishoriöl and delivered to Golgotterath.{{EG|Heron Spear}} This is at least 2,000 years after the Heron Spear was first taken to Ishoriöl (as the spear was said to reside there for "millennia"<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Heron Spear'</ref>).
* '''777'''—Cet’ingira, or Mekeritrig, reveals the Incû-Holoinas, or Min-Uroikas, to the School of Mangaecca.{{EG|Golgotterath}}{{EG|Mangaecca}}{{EG|Mekeritrig}}
* '''c. 800'''—The fortifying of Golgotterath begins. [[Gwergiruh]], the accursed Gatehouse of [[Ûbil Maw]], the Extrinsic Gate, is raised.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Gwergiruh'</ref>
* '''809'''—The City of [[Cenei]] is founded.{{EG|''Annals of Cenei, The''}}
* '''811'''—[[Akksersia]] is founded by [[Salaweärn I]], following the dissolution of the [[Cond]] Yoke, originally confined to the city of [[Myclai]].{{EG|Akksersia}} The Cond were pastoralists from the Near [[Istyuli Plains]].{{EG|Condic}}
* '''c. 820'''—Approximate date of the birth of [[Avalunsil]].<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Avalunsil'</ref>
* '''825'''—Nonman Tutelage ends with the Expulsion, following the famed Rape of [[Anasûrimbor Omindalea|Omindalea]].{{EG|Nonmen Tutelage}}
* '''c. 840'''—Avalunsil kills Symaul, the Skettic chieftain who murdered her father, [[Wulta-Ongorean]], with a fish knife. She is proclaimed Empress of Ûmeria.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Avalunsil'</ref>
* '''''c.'' 850'''—The city of [[Kelmeöl]] is founded as a trading stronghold by Akksersian colonists, these people would come to be known as the [[Meöri Empire|Meöri]].{{EG|Meöri Empire}}<ref group="Notes">Exact location unclear, but somewhere north of the River Wernma. It is on the South bank of the Sea of Cerish. (Vosa River Basin is not identified).</ref>
* '''c. 860'''—Avalunsil is killed by a jealous suitor after she spurns his proposal of marraige.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Avalunsil'</ref>
* '''917'''—The Cond tribesmen of [[Aulyanau|Aulyanau the Conqueror]] defeat Ancient Ûmeria at the [[Battle of the River Axau]]. The Cond Yoke collapses rapidly leading to a second period of Trysean dominance.{{EG|Kûniüri}}
* '''927'''—The Cond tribesmen of Aulyanau the Conqueror defeat Ara-Etrith (“New Etrith”), latter called Atrithau, and settle several Cond tribes in the vicinity. These tribes quickly abandon their pastoral ways and assimilate into Aumris culture.{{EG|Eämnor}}<ref group="Notes">Here the Cond Yoke is still around in 927, but falls shortly after 917 in Ûmeria (by 1128 at the latest), but in Akksersia, the Yoke falls before 811. They are pastoral tribes, so they were in the east ''c.'' 800, but in the west ''c.'' 900.</ref>
* '''''c.'' 1000'''—[[Ingusharotep II]], Old Dynasty Shigek King who conquered the [[Kyranae Plains]], is born.{{EG|Ingusharotep II}}
* '''''c.'' 1005'''—[[Noshainrau|Noshainrau the White,]] founding Grandmaster of the Gnostic School of [[Sohonc]] and author of the ''[[Interrogations]],'' the first elaboration of the Gnosis by Men, is born.{{EG|Noshainrau the White}}
* '''1021'''—[[Borswelka I]] declared King of the Meöri, an aggressive, militaristic city-state.{{EG|Meöri Empire}}
* '''1023'''—Beginning of the Old Invishi period in [[Nilnamesh]], when Nilnamesh was united under a series of aggressively expansionist Kings based in [[Invishi]].{{EG|Nilnamesh}}
* '''1072'''—Noshainrau the White, founding Grandmaster of Sohonc, dies at age 67.{{EG|Noshainrau the White}}<ref group="Notes">However, according to ''The False Sun'' the Sohonc was founded between 574-688, so Noshainrau can not have been the founding Grandmaster.</ref>
* '''''c.'' 1080'''—Ingusharotep II, Old Dynasty Shigek King, dies at age 80.{{EG|Ingusharotep II}}
* '''''c.'' 1086'''—[[Shaeönanra]], Grandvizier of the Mangaecca, is born (or this is the year he became Grandvizier, it is unclear).{{EG|Shaeönanra}}{{EG|Shauriatas}}<ref group="Notes">If this is the date of his birth, then he was already Grandvizier at age 37 in 1123.</ref>
* '''1111'''—Shaeönanra and Cet’ingira overcome the glamour around Golgotterath. At some point in the next several years, the Inchoroi [[Aurax]] and [[Aurang]] are released.<ref>''Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Consult'</ref>
* '''1119'''—Shaeönanra and Aurang defeat [[Titirga]], Grandmaster of the Sohonc.
* '''12th c.'''—Various Ketyai tribes begin asserting their independence from Shigek on the Kyranae Plains, and the God-Kings of Shigek start waging incessant war.{{EG|Shigek}}
* '''1104'''—[[Borswelka II]] King of Meöri, grandson of Borswelka I, dies. Meöri controls most of the [[River Vosa]] Basin and had established trading contacts with [[Shir]] to the south through a series of forts along the [[River Wernma]].{{EG|Meöri Empire}}
* '''1123'''—Shaeönanra, Grandvizier of the Mangaecca, claims to have rediscovered a means of saving the souls of those damned by sorcery. Mangaecca was promptly outlawed for impiety. Mangaecca abandon Sauglish and flee to Golgotterath.{{EG|Mangaecca}}{{EG|Shaeönanra}}
* '''13th c.'''—The city-state of Shir on the [[River Maurat]], subdues all the cities of Seto-Annaria.{{EG|Shiradi Empire}}
* '''1228'''—Beginning of the [[Scintya]] Yoke, the migratory invasions of White Norsirai Scintya, in the area of River Aumris and Ara-Etrith, latter Atrithau.{{EG|Eämnor}}{{EG|Kûniüri}}
* '''1251'''—The First Great Sranc War. Akksersia is the largest of the Norsirai nations, incorporating almost all the White Norsirai tribes save those of the Istyuli Plains, covering length of the [[River Tywanrae]], the [[Plains of Gâl]] and the entire north shore of the [[Cerish|Cerish Sea]].{{EG|Akksersia}}
* '''14th c.'''—Trysean annals begin referring to Shaeönanra as Shauriatas.{{EG|Shaeönanra}}
* '''1322'''—[[Anzumarapata II]], Nilnameshi King of Invishi, inflicts a crushing defeat on the Shigeki, and transplants hundreds of thousands of indigent Nilnameshi on the [[Plains of Heshor]], or [[Amoteu]].{{EG|Nilnamesh}}{{EG|Amoteu}}
* '''1326'''—Anzumarapata II, Nilnameshi King of Invishi, defeats the Shigeki again, at compels tribute for some thirty years.{{EG|Nilnamesh}}
* '''1349'''—Shigeki re-conquers the Middle-Lands of Amoteu.{{EG|Amoteu}}<ref group="Notes">So the Nilnamesh control Amoteu for 27 years, from 1322 to 1349, and compel Shigeki tribute for 23 years? From 1326 to 1349.</ref>
* '''1378'''—[[Anasûrimbor Nanor-Ukkerja I]], “Hammer of Heaven” (Kûniüric ''nanor ukkerja'' from Ûmeritic ''nanar hukisha''), the first Anasûrimbor High King, is born.{{EG|Nanor-Ukkerja I}}
* '''1381'''—End of the Scintya Yoke and emergence of [[Eämnor]] as one of the preeminent nations of the Ancient North.{{EG|Eämnor}}
* '''c. 1400'''—Zeum is unified by [[Mbotetulu]], [[Satakhan]] of the Ojogi Dynasty.
* '''15th c.'''—Xiuhianni invaders from [[Jekhia|Jekk]], ravaged the [[Shiradi Empire]] and Shir was razed to the ground. The survivors move the capital to [[Aöknyssus]], and after some twenty years manage to oust the Eännean invaders.{{EG|Shiradi Empire}}
* '''1408'''—Anasûrimbor Nanor-Ukkerja I defeats Scintya, seizes the Ur-Throne in Trysë and declares himself the first High King of [[Kûniüri]], at age 30.{{EG|Anasûrimbor Dynasty}}{{EG|Kûniüri}}{{EG|Nanor-Ukkerja I}}<ref group="Notes">So in Eämnor, Scintya fell in 1381, but to the East only 27 years latter in 1408?</ref>
* '''1440'''—Sranc incursions across the Leash into [[Wuor]], the north-western province of Kûniüri, begin.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Far Wuor'</ref>
* '''1450'''—Birth of [[Iswa]], the founder of the [[Iswazi]] doctrine of sorcery, in [[Domyot]].<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Isaw'</ref>
* '''1556'''—Anasûrimbor Nanor-Ukkerja I dies at age 178, his long life reputedly the result of the Nonman blood in his veins. In the 148 years of his reign, he had extended Kûniüri to the [[Yimaleti Mountains]] in the north, to the westernmost coasts of the Cerish Sea in the east, to [[Sakarpus]] in the south, and to the [[Demua Mountains]] in the west. At his death, he divided this empire between his sons, creating [[Aörsi]] and [[Sheneor]] in addition to Kûniüri proper.{{EG|Aörsi}}{{EG|Kûniüri}}{{EG|Nanor-Ukkerja I}}
* '''1572'''—End of the Old Invishi period, of aggressively expansionist Kings, in Nilnamesh.{{EG|Nilnamesh}}
* '''1591'''—God-King [[Mithoser II]] of Shigek is decisively defeated by the Kyraneans at [[Narakit]], and Shigek begins its long tenure as a tributary to greater powers.{{EG|Shigek}} Shigek loses regional dominance over Amoteu, the [[Jarti]] attempt to reassert ancestral control, with disastrous consequences. The resulting war gave rise to a brief Amoti Empire, which reached the length of the [[Betmulla Mountains]] to the frontier of the [[Carathay Desert]].{{EG|Amoteu}}
* '''1601'''—The fortress of [[Dagliash]] is raised by High King [[Nanor-Mikhus]] of Aörsi, upon the ruins of Viri.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Dagliash'</ref>
* '''1680'''—Far Wuor is finally abandoned to the Sranc, with a new defensive line drawn up to the south-east.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Far Wuor'</ref>
* '''1703'''—The Middle-Lands, the area of Amoteu, fall to the [[Kyraneas]].{{EG|Amoteu}}
* '''1798'''—[[Girgalla]], ancient Kûniüric poet famed for his ''[[Epic of Sauglish]],'' is born.{{EG|Girgalla}}
* '''''c.'' 1800'''—The [[Scarlet Spires]], originally called the Surartu, secured the river fortress of [[Kiz]] in [[Carythusal]].{{EG|Scarlet Spires}}
* '''1841'''—Girgalla, ancient Kûniüric poet, dies at age 43.{{EG|Girgalla}}
* '''''c.'' 1896'''—[[Ajencis]], father of syllogistic logic and algebra, is born in the Kyranean capital of [[Mehtsonc]]. He would write ''[[Theophysics]],'' ''[[The First Analytic of Men]]'' and ''[[The Third Analytic of Men]].''{{EG|Ajencis}}
* '''''c.'' 1904'''—At age 8, Ajencis was granted Protection by the Kyranean High King, allowing him to say anything without fear of reprisal, even to the High King.{{EG|Ajencis}}
* '''1966'''—[[Ingoswitu]], far antique Kûniüric philosopher, is born. He would write ''[[Dialogia]],'' and was critiqued by Ajencis.{{EG|Ingoswitu}}
* '''1991'''—Horrific plagues inflict the Kyranean capital of Mehtsonc.{{EG|Ajencis}}
* '''2000'''—Ajencis suffers a stroke and died at the venerable age of 103.{{EG|Ajencis}}
* '''2050'''—Ingoswitu, far antique Kûniüric philosopher dies at age 84.{{EG|Ingoswitu}}
* '''2056'''—[[Anasûrimbor Mygella]], Hero-King of Aörsi, whose deeds are recounted in ''[[The Sagas]],'' is born.{{EG|Mygella, Anasûrimbor}}
* '''2089'''—[[Anasûrimbor Celmomas II]], last High King of Kûniüri, is born.{{EG|Celmomas II, Anasûrimbor}} [[Seswatha]], founder of the School of [[Mandate]], is born to a caste-menial Trysean bronzesmith.{{EG|Seswatha}}
* '''2092'''—[[Anasûrimbor Nimeric]], High King of Ancient Aörsi before its destruction in the [[Apocalypse]], is born.{{EG|Nimeric, Anasûrimbor}}
* '''''c.'' 2100'''—[[Uthgai]], folklore hero and Scylvendi King-of-Tribes during the Apocalypse, is born.{{EG|Uthgai}}
* '''2104'''—At age 15, Seswatha becomes the youngest sorcerer of rank in the history of the Sohonc.{{EG|Seswatha}} [[Anasûrimbor Ganrelka II]], successor of Celmomas II and last reigning High King of Kûniüri, is born.{{EG|Ganrelka II, Anasûrimbor}}
* '''2109'''—[[Anaxophus V]], Kyranean High King, is born.{{EG|Anaxophus V}}
* '''2111'''—Anasûrimbor Mygella, famed Hero-King of Aörsi, dies at age 46.{{EG|Mygella, Anasûrimbor}}
* '''2115'''—[[Ginsil]], wife of General [[En-Kaujalau]] in ''The Sagas,'' who pretended to be her husband to fool the assassins coming to kill him, is born.{{EG|Ginsil}}
* '''2118'''—[[Shikol]], King of Ancient [[Xerash]], famed for sentencing [[Inri Sejenus]] to death, is born.{{EG|Shikol}}
* '''2119'''—[[Anasûrimbor Nau-Cayûti]], youngest son of Anasûrimbor Celmomas II and his most prized wife [[Sharal]], is born. Legends have long circulated that Nau-Cayûti was in fact Seswatha’s son.{{EG|Nau-Cayûti}}{{EG|Seswatha}}

====The Apocalypse ''(2123-2155)''====
* '''2123'''—Nonman Siqû inform the Grandmaster of the Sohonc that the Mangaecca, or [[Consult]] as they had come to be called, had uncovered lost Inchoroi secrets that would lead to the world’s destruction. Seswatha in turn convinced Anasûrimbor Celmomas to declare war on Golgotterath, known as the Great Ordeal.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Ordeal, the}}
* '''2124'''—The Great Ordeal fight Consult forces on the Plains of [[Agongorea]], the battle was indecisive. Celmomas and his allies wintered in [[Dagliash]].{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2125'''<ref group="Notes">This assumes the year starts in the winter or at the beginning of spring.</ref>—The following spring, the Great Ordeal ford the [[River Sursa]], catching their foe unawares. The Consult withdrew to Golgotterath, and so began what would be called the Great Investiture. For six years the Ordeal attempted to starve the Consult into submission, to no avail. Every assault proved disastrous.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2131'''—Celmomas abandons the Holy War following a dispute with King Nimeric of Aörsi.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2132'''—Consult legions, apparently utilizing a vast subterranean network of tunnels, appear in the Ring Mountains to the rear of the Ordeal. The coalition host is all but destroyed. Embittered by the loss of his sons, Nil’giccas, the Nonman King of Ishterebinth, withdraws altogether, leaving the Aörsi to war alone.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2133'''—The Aörsi are defeated at the [[Passes of Amnerlot]], and Dagliash was lost soon after. King Nimeric withdraws to his capital of [[Shiarau]].{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2134'''—[[Burning of the White Ships]]; falling back before the Consult legions, Anasûrimbor Nimeric dispatches the Aörsic fleet to shelter in the Kûniüri port of [[Aesorea]]. Mere days after its arrival, it is burned by agents unknown.{{EG|Burning of the White Ships}} Celmomas acknowledges his folly and mobilizes to relieve Aörsi King Nimeric at Shiarau.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2135'''—Anasûrimbor Nimeric is mortally wounded in the [[Battle of Hamuir]], and dies at age 43.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Nimeric, Anasûrimbor}}
* '''2136'''—Shiarau capital of Aörsi falls in spring, and Aörsi is destroyed. The [[Worldhorn]], a ceremonial sorcerous artifact, is lost with Shiarau.{{EG|Aörsi}}{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Worldhorn}}
* '''2137'''—Nau-Cayûti manages to rout the Consult at the [[Battle of Ossirish]], where he earns the name Murswagga, or “Dragonslayer,” for killing [[Tanhafut|Tanhafut the Red]]. His next victory, within sight of Shiarau’s ruins, is more complete still. The Consult’s remaining Sranc and Bashrag flee across the River Sursa.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Nau-Cayûti}}
* '''2139'''—Nau-Cayûti besieges and recaptures Dagliash, and launches several spectacular raids across the Plains of Agongorea.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2140'''—Nau-Cayûti’s beloved concubine, [[Aulisi]], is abducted by Sranc marauders and taken to Golgotterath. According to ''The Sagas'' Seswatha was able to convince the Prince (who was once his student) that she could be rescued from the Incû-Holoinas, and the two of them embarked on an expedition that is almost certainly apocryphal. Mandate commentators dispute the account found in ''The Sagas,'' where they successfully return with both Aulisi and the Heron Spear, claiming that Aulisi was never found. Whatever happened, at least two things are certain: the Heron Spear was in fact recovered, and Nau-Cayûti died shortly after at age 21 (apparently poisoned by his first wife, [[Iëva]]).{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Heron Spear}}{{EG|Nau-Cayûti}} He is actually poisoned by his first wife, Iëva (later executed for the crime) and only given the semblance of death. He is retrieved by Aurang and borne to Golgotterath, where he is tortured for his knowledge of the Heron Spear.<ref>''[[The White-Luck Warrior]]''</ref>
* '''2141'''—The Consult return to the offensive. At the [[Battle of Skothera]], the Sranc hordes are crushed by General En-Kaujalau, though he died of mysterious causes within weeks of this victory (according to ''The Sagas,'' he was another victim of Iëva and her poisons, but again this is disputed by Mandate scholars).{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2142'''—General [[Sag-Marmau]] inflicts yet another crushing defeat on Aurang and his Consult legions, and by fall he had hounded the remnant of their horde to the Gates of Golgotterath itself. This siege is known as the Second Great Investiture.{{EG|Apocalypse}} The [[Chorae Hail]] is unleashed when Celmomas orders the Sohonc to attack the Intrinsic Gate of Golgotterath, resulting in the deaths of sixty-one Sohonc sorcerers, more than a third of the order. Seswatha was criticised for obeying the command, which imperilled the Investiture.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Chorae Hail'</ref>
* '''2143'''—In spring the [[No-God]] is summoned. Across the world, Sranc, Bashrag, and Wracu, all the obscene progeny of the Inchoroi, hearkened to his call. Sag-Marmau and the greater glory of Kûniüri are annihilated. All Men could sense his dread presence on the horizon, and all infants were born dead. The 11 years when all infants were still born comes to be known as the [[Years of the Crib]]. Anasûrimbor Celmomas II had little difficulty gathering support for his Second Ordeal. Nil’giccas and Celmomas were reconciled. Across Eärwa, hosts of Men began marching toward Kûniüri.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Years of the Crib}}
* '''2146'''—[[Battle of Eleneöt Fields]] is fought between the Horde of the No-God and the Second Ordeal on Kûniüri’s northeastern frontier. Despite having assembled the greatest host of their age, Anasûrimbor Celmomas and his allies are unprepared for the vast numbers of Sranc, Bashrag, and Wracu gathered by the No-God and his Consult slaves. The battle is an unmitigated catastrophe, signaling the eventual destruction of Norsirai civilization. With his dying words Anasûrimbor Celmomas II predicts the return of an Anasûrimbor at “the end of the world” to Seswatha. This would come to be known as the [[Celmomian Prophecy]]. Celmomas II dies at age 57. The Heron Spear, which could not be used because the No-God refused to give battle, was lost.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Battle of Eleneöt Fields}}{{EG|Celmomas II, Anasûrimbor}}{{EG|Celmomian Prophecy}}{{EG|Heron Spear}}{{EG|Kûniüri}} Anasûrimbor Ganrelka II becomes the last reigning High King of Kûniüri.{{EG|Ganrelka II, Anasûrimbor}}
* '''2147'''—All the ancient cities of the Aumris are destroyed, including Trysë and Sauglish.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Knights of Trysë}}{{EG|Kûniüri}}{{EG|Sauglish}}{{EG|Trysë}} Four Ûmeri copies of the ''Isûphiryas'' of these were destroyed along with the Library of Sauglish.{{EG|Great Library of Sauglish}}{{EG|Library of Sauglish}} The fifth is saved by Seswatha, who latter delivered it to the scribes of the [[Three Seas]].{{EG|''Isûphiryas''}} The surviving Kûniüri are either enslaved or scattered.{{EG|Kûniüri}} Ganrelka II, last reigning High King of Kûniüri dies at age 43, ending the [[Anasûrimbor Dynasty]].{{EG|Anasûrimbor Dynasty}}{{EG|Ganrelka II, Anasûrimbor}} Ginsil, wife of General En-Kaujalau, dies at age 32.{{EG|Ginsil}} The Nonmen of Injor-Niyas retreat to Ishterebinth.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2148'''—Eämnor is laid waste, though its capital, Atrithau, survived.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Eämnor}}
* '''2149'''—Akksersia, including the capital, Myclai, falls after three disastrous defeats.{{EG|Akksersia}}{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Myclai}} [[Harmant]] falls as well. {{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2150'''—Kelmeöl falls and the Meöri Empire falls with it.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Kelmeöl}}{{EG|Meöri Empire}}
* '''2151'''—[[Inweära]] falls, though the city of Sakarpus was spared. In autumn, the remnant Meöri and the Nonmen of Cil-Aujas are victorious against the Consult at the [[Battle of Kathol Pass]].{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2152'''—In spring, the Meöri turn on their benefactors and sack the ancient Nonman Mansion of Cil-Aujas.{{EG|Apocalypse}}
* '''2153'''—Forces of the No-God inflict a disastrous defeat on the Shiradi at the [[Battle of Nurubal]]. The next two hundred years of chaos and internecine warfare effectively destroyed what remained of the Shiradi Empire and its central institutions.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Shiradi Empire}}
* '''2154'''—The [[Battle of Mehsarunath]] is fought between the Kyraneas and the host of the No-God on the [[Attong Plateau]]. Aurang, the No-God’s Horde-General, won the battle, but the Kyranean High King, Anaxophus V, is able to escape with much of his host intact. He abandoned Mehtsonc and [[Sumna]] to the Scylvendi. The Tusk is evacuated and brought to Ancient Invishi in Nilnamesh. Mehtsonc is destroyed, sealing the fate of Kyraneas. Anaxophus V reveals to Seswatha that he rescued the Heron Spear from the Fields of Eleneöt in 2146.{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Battle of Mehsarunath}}{{EG|Heron Spear}}{{EG|Kyraneas}}{{EG|Mehtsonc}}
* '''2155'''—The [[Second Battle of Mengedda]], Anaxophus V and his southern tributaries and allies make their victorious stand against the Horde of the No-God. Seswatha slays [[Skafra]] the Wracu. Wielding the Heron Spear Anaxophus V strikes down the No-God. Free of his terrible will, his Sranc, Bashrag, and Wracu slaves disperse.{{EG|Anaxophus V}}{{EG|Apocalypse}}{{EG|Battle of Mengedda, the Second}}{{EG|Heron Spear}}{{EG|Mengedda}}{{EG|Skafra}} Pestilence swept up from the No-God after his defeat causing the [[Indigo Plague]], one of the worst in recorded history.{{EG|Indigo Plague}} The end of the Apocalypse marks the end of Far Antiquity, and the beginning of [[Near Antiquity]].{{EG|Far Antiquity}}{{EG|Near Antiquity}}

===Near Antiquity ''(2156-3351)''===
* '''2156'''—Anaxophus V, Kyranean High King, dies at age 47.{{EG|Anaxophus V}} Seswatha founds the School of Mandate.{{EG|Mandate, School of}}
* '''2157'''—The Great Pestilence, also known as the Indigo Plague, a devastating pandemic sweeps Eärwa following the death of the No-God.{{EG|Great Pestilence}} The tower of [[Atyersus]] is founded by Seswatha as the primary stronghold of the Mandate.{{EG|Atyersus}}

====Age of Warring Cities ''(''c.'' 2158-2477)''====
* '''''c.'' 2158'''—The [[Age of Warring Cities]] begins. Following the dissolution of Kyraneas, cities of the Kyranae Plains are characterized by perpetual warfare.{{EG|Age of Warring Cities}} This allowed Amoteu independence, though now the Xerashi, the descendants of Anzumarapata’s settlers, had become its primary competitors.{{EG|Amoteu}}
* '''2158'''—The tower [[Attrempus]], sister fortress of Atyersus, is founded by Seswatha and the nascent School of Mandate.{{EG|Attrempus}}
* '''''c.'' 2159'''—Inri Sejenus, the Latter Prophet, is born.{{EG|Inri Sejenus}}
* '''2168'''—Seswatha, founder of the School of Mandate, dies at age 79.{{EG|Seswatha}}
* '''''c.'' 2170'''—Uthgai, Scylvendi King-of-Tribes during the Apocalypse, dies at approximately age 70.{{EG|Uthgai}}
* '''2198'''—King Shikol of Ancient Xerash, sentences Inri Sejenus to death. Shikol is 80 and Inri Sejenus is 39.{{EG|Inri Sejenus}}{{EG|Shikol}}
* '''2202'''—King Shikol dies at age 84.{{EG|Shikol}} Inri Sejenus is said to ascend to the [[Nail of Heaven]] at age 43.{{EG|Inri Sejenus}}
* '''2300'''—[[Teres Ansansius]], most famed theologian of the early [[Thousand Temples]], is born. He would go on to write, ''[[The City of Men]],'' ''[[The Limping Pilgrim]],'' and ''[[Five Letters to All]]'' which are revered by Shrial scholars.{{EG|Ansansius, Teres}}
* '''2304'''—[[Ekyannus I]], first “institutional” [[Shriah]] of the Thousand Temples, and author of ''[[44 Epistles]],'' is born.{{EG|Ekyannus I}}
* '''2338'''—[[Stajanas II]], “Philosopher-Emperor” of Cenei, author of ''[[Ruminations]],'' is born.{{EG|Stajanas II}}
* '''2349'''—The city of Cenei conquers [[Gielgath]], sealing its regional dominance. In the ensuing decades the [[Ceneian Empire|Ceneians]] under [[Xercallas II]] would secure the remnants of what had once been Kyraneas. Xercallas’s successors continued his aggressive, expansionist policies, first pacifying the Norsirai tribes of [[Cepalor]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2350'''—Kiz, home of the Scarlet Spires, is severely damaged in an earthquake. The fortress is covered with red enamel tiles in the reconstruction, thus leading to the School’s now-famous moniker.{{EG|Scarlet Spires}}
* '''2351'''—Teres Ansansius, famed theologian of the early Thousand Temples, dies at approximately age 51.{{EG|Ansansius, Teres}}
* '''2372'''—Ekyannus I, first “institutional” Shriah of the Thousand Temples, dies at age 68.{{EG|Ekyannus I}}
* '''2390'''—The [[Zealot Wars]], a prolonged religious conflict between the early [[Inrithism|Inrithi]] and the [[Kiünnat]], begin.{{EG|Inrithism}}{{EG|Zealot Wars}}
* '''2395'''—Stajanas II, “Philosopher-Emperor” of Cenei, dies at age 57.{{EG|Stajanas II}}<ref group="Notes">This is in '''contradiction''' to ''‘Ruminations’'' (see 2431 for details)</ref> [[Pirras Boksarias]], Ceneian Emperor who standardized trading protocols within the empire and established a thriving system of markets in its major cities, is born.{{EG|Boksarias, Pirras}}
* '''2397'''—Shigek falls to Cenei after three consecutive wars.{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2412'''—Stajanas II, “Philosopher-Emperor” of Cenei, begins ruling.{{EG|''Ruminations''}}<ref group="Notes">This is in '''contradiction''' to ‘Stajanas II’ (see 2431 for details)</ref>
* '''2414'''—General [[Naxentas]] of Cenei conquers [[Enathpaneah]], Xerash, and Amoteu. He then staged a successful coup and declared himself Emperor of Cenei.{{EG|Amoteu}}{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2415'''—Naxentas, self declared Emperor of Cenei, is assassinated.{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2431'''—The reign of Stajanas II, “Philosopher-Emperor” of Cenei, ends.{{EG|''Ruminations''}}<ref group="Notes">There is a '''contradiction''' in the text. According to ‘Stajanas II’ he was born in 2338 and died in 2395, but according to ''‘Ruminations’'' he ruled from 2412 to 2431. If we accept his birth year as 2338 then he would have been 57 in 2395, 74 in 2412 and 93 in 2431. An age of 93 at death seems possible. Additionally, according to ‘Ceneian Empire’ General Naxentas led a successful coup in 2414 and was then killed in 2415. If Stajanas II ruled 2412-2431, then he ruled for 2 years, was overthrown, and then regained the throne after Naxentas was killed. If Stajanas II died in 2395, then Naxentas rebels in the 19th year of Stajanas II’s successor. The situation remains unclear.</ref>
* '''2432'''—[[Ekyannus III]], “the Golden,” Shriah of the Thousand Temples, is born.{{EG|Ekyannus III, “the Golden”}}
* '''2437'''—Pirras Boksarias, Ceneian Emperor, dies at age 42.{{EG|Boksarias, Pirras}}
* '''2456'''—[[Triamis the Great]], first [[Aspect-Emperor]] of the Ceneian Empire, is born.{{EG|Triamis the Great}}
* '''2458'''—Inrithi fanatics lead the province of Amoteu in a vicious rebellion against Cenei. As punishment, Emperor [[Siaxas II]] butchers the inhabitants of [[Kyudea]] and razes the city to the ground.{{EG|Amoteu}}
* '''2466'''—[[Memgowa]], famed near antique [[Zeüm]]i sage and philosopher, is born. He would later write ''[[Celestial Aphorisms]]'' and ''[[The Book of Divine Acts]].''{{EG|Memgowa}}
* '''2469'''—Part of the Zealot Wars, Sumna capitulates to Shrial forces, but hostilities continue.{{EG|Inrithism}}

====Age of Cenei ''(2478-3351)''====
* '''2478'''—Triamis I (the Great) is anointed Emperor at age 22.{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}{{EG|Triamis the Great}}{{EG|Inrithism}} Triamis I enacts the constitution governing the division of powers between the Imperium and the Thousand Temples, leading to the end of the Zealot Wars.{{EG|Inrithism}}{{EG|Zealot Wars}} This year marks the beginning of the [[Age of Cenei]], also known as the Ceneian Golden Age.{{EG|Age of Cenei}}{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}<ref group="Notes">There is a '''contradiction''' in the text. ‘Age of Cenei’ claims the conquest of Nilnamesh occurs 2478. While ‘Ceneian Empire’ and ‘Nilnamesh’ both state this happened in 2483. The most likely solution is that the Age of Cenei begins (when the Zealot Wars end) in 2478 with the ascension of Triamis the Great, as stated in Ceneian Empire (not with the conquest of Nilnamesh), and Nilnamesh is conquered in 2483. The ‘Age of Cenei’ entry is then in error.</ref>
* '''2483'''—Triamis I defeats [[Sarnagiri V]], leading a coalition of Nilnameshi Princes. Nilnamesh becomes a Ceneian province for more than a thousand years.{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}{{EG|Nilnamesh}}
* '''2484'''—Triamis I conquers [[Cingulat]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2485'''—Triamis I defeated a great Zeümi host at [[Amarah]], and would have invaded the Satyothi nation had not mutinies among his homesick troops prevented him. He spent the next decade consolidating his gains, and striving against the internecine religious violence between followers of the traditional Kiünnat sects and the growing numbers of “Inrithi.”{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2500'''—Shriah Ekyannus III (then age 68), formally institutionalizes the so-called Emperor Cult. Triamis the Great (age 44), in the twenty-third year of his rule, takes the title Aspect-Emperor, which is adopted by all his successors.{{EG|Aspect-Emperor}}
* '''2505'''—Triamis I converts under Ekyannus III and declares Inrithism the official state religion of the Ceneian Empire. He spent the next ten years putting down religious rebellions.{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}{{EG|Cults}}{{EG|Ekyannus III, “the Golden”}}{{EG|Inrithism}}{{EG|Thousand Temples}}{{EG|Triamis the Great}}
* '''2506'''—Memgowa, near antique Zeümi sage and philosopher, dies at age 40. Memgowa is primarily known in the Three Seas for his ''Celestial Aphorisms'' and ''The Book of Divine Acts.''{{EG|Memgowa}}
* '''2508'''—Triamis I invades and occupies [[Cironj]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2511'''—Triamis I invades and occupies [[Nron]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}} Ekyannus III “the Golden” founds the [[Shrial Knights]], a monastic military order charged with prosecuting the will of the Shriah.{{EG|Shrial Knights}}
* '''2516'''—Ekyannus III “the Golden” dies at age 84.{{EG|Ekyannus III, “the Golden”}}
* '''2518'''—Triamis I conquers [[High Ainon|Ainon]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2519'''—Triamis I conquers [[Cengemis]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2525'''—Triamis I conquers [[Annand]].{{EG|Ceneian Empire}}
* '''2568'''—The Triamic Walls, [[Caraskand]]’s outermost fortifications, are raised by Triamis the Great.{{EG|Triamic Walls}}
* '''2577'''—Triamis the Great dies at age 121.{{EG|Triamis the Great}}
* '''2789'''—[[Muretetis]], ancient Ceneian scholar-slave, is born. He will go on to write ''[[Axioms and Theorems]],'' the founding text of Three Seas geometry.{{EG|Muretetis}}
* '''2847'''—[[Xius]], great Ceneian poet and playwright, famed for ''[[The Trucian Dramas]],'' is born.{{EG|Xius}}
* '''2864'''—Muretetis, ancient Ceneian scholar-slave, dies at age 75.{{EG|Muretetis}}
* '''2870'''—[[Protathis]], famed near antique poet of Ceneian descent, is born. He will go on to write many works, including ''[[The Goat’s Heart]],'' ''[[One Hundred Heavens]],'' and the magisterial ''[[Aspirations]].''{{EG|Protathis}}
* '''2875'''—[[Ontillas]], near antique Ceneian satirist most famous for ''[[On the Folly of Men]],'' is born.{{EG|Ontillas}}
* '''2881'''—[[Olekaros]], Ceneian slave-scholar of Cironji descent, famed for his ''[[Avowals]],'' is born.{{EG|Olekaros}}
* '''2914'''—Xius, great Ceneian poet and playwright, dies at age 67.{{EG|Xius}}
* '''2922'''—Protathis, famed near antique poet of Ceneian descent, dies at age 52.{{EG|Protathis}}
* '''2933'''—Ontillas, near antique Ceneian satirist, dies at age 58.{{EG|Ontillas}}
* '''2956'''—Olekaros, Ceneian slave-scholar of Cironji descent, dies at age 75.{{EG|Olekaros}}
* '''2981'''—[[Gaeterius]], Ceneian slave-scholar, is born. He will go on to write commentaries on ''The Chronicle of the Tusk'' collected under the title ''[[Contemplations on the Indentured Soul]].''{{EG|Gaeterius}}
* '''3045'''—Gaeterius, Ceneian slave-scholar, dies at age 64.{{EG|Gaeterius}}
* '''3081'''—[[Casidas]], famed philosopher and historian of Near Antiquity, best known for his magisterial ''[[The Annals of Cenei]]'', is born.{{EG|Casidas}}
* '''3142'''—Casidas, famed philosopher and historian of Near Antiquity, dies at age 61.{{EG|Casidas}}
* '''3174'''—[[Hatatian]], infamous author of the ''[[Exhortations]],'' a work that eschews traditional Inrithi values and espouses an ethos of unprincipled self-promotion, is born.{{EG|Hatatian}}
* '''3211'''—Hatatian, infamous author of the ''Exhortations,'' dies at age 37.{{EG|Hatatian}} [[Opparitha]], near antique Cengemian moralist most famous for his ''[[On the Carnal]],'' is born.{{EG|Opparitha}}
* '''3256'''—[[Throseanis]], late Ceneian dramatist, famed for his ''[[Triamis Imperator]],'' a dramatic account of the life of Triamis I, is born.{{EG|Throseanis}}
* '''3299'''—Opparitha, near antique Cengemian moralist, dies at age 88.{{EG|Opparitha}}
* '''3317'''—Throseanis, late Ceneian dramatist, dies at age 61.{{EG|Throseanis}} [[Sarothesser I]], founder of High Ainon, is born.{{EG|Sarothesser I}}
* '''3351'''—Cenei, a city of the Kyranae Plains, was destroyed by the Scylvendi under [[Horiötha]].{{EG|Cenei}}{{EG|Ceneian Empire}} The Heron Spear was lost in the attack.{{EG|Heron Spear}} The [[Sack of Cenei]] marks the end of both the Age of Cenei{{EG|Age of Cenei}} and Near Antiquity.{{EG|Near Antiquity}}[[Batathent]], a fortress-temple dating back to pre-classical Kyraneas, is destroyed by the Scylvendi shortly after the fall of Cenei.{{EG|Batathent}}

===Present Era ''(3352- )''===
(The period after Near Antiquity is not named in the text).
* '''3371'''—Shriah [[Diagol]], known for his cruel excesses, holds the Seat.{{EG|Writ of Psata-Antyu}}
* '''3372'''—Cenei General [[Maurelta]] surrenders to Sarothesser I at the [[Battle of Charajat]]. This marks the traditional collapse of the Ceneian Empire.{{EG|Ceneian Empire}} Sarothesser I ascends the [[Assurkamp Throne]] as the first Ainoni King, at age 30.{{EG|Sarothesser I}}{{EG|High Ainon}} Following the fall of the Ceneian Empire, Cengemis gains independence,{{EG|Cengemis}} in Nilnamesh, the New Invishi period begins.{{EG|Nilnamesh}}
* '''3374'''—[[Conriya]] is founded around Aöknyssus, the ancient capital of Shir.{{EG|Conriya}}
* '''3383'''—Shriah Diagol, known for his cruel excesses, is assassinated after 12 years.{{EG|Writ of Psata-Antyu}}
* '''3386'''—[[Writ of Psata-Antyu]] is issued by the high clergy of the Thousand Temples at the Council of Antyu to limit the power of the Shriah. The Writ was motivated by the cruel excesses of Shriah Diagol.{{EG|Writ of Psata-Antyu}}
* '''3402'''—Sarothesser I, first king of High Ainon, after ruling for 55 years, dies at age 85.{{EG|Sarothesser I}}
* '''3411'''—Beginning of the [[House Trimus|Trimus]] Emperors’ rule of [[Nansur Empire|Nansur]] (the traditional name for the district surrounding [[Momemn]]). Under the Trimus Emperors, Nansur unified the Kyranae Plains.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}
* '''3470'''—[[Zerxei Triamarius I]], first of the Zerxei Emperors of Nansur, is born.{{EG|Triamarius I}}
* '''3508'''—Lasting for 97 years, the Trimus Dynasty in Nansur ends when [[Trimus Meniphas I]] is assassinated.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Triamarius I}}
* '''3511'''—At age 41, Triamarius I is acclaimed by the Imperial Army as the first [[House Zerxei|Zerxei]] Emperor of Nansur, beginning the Zerxei Dynasty.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Triamarius I}}{{EG|Zerxei, House}}
* '''3517'''—Triamarius I, first Zerxei Emperor of Nansur, dies at age 47 after ruling Nansur for 6 years.{{EG|Triamarius I}}
* '''3539'''—Nansur conquers Shigek.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}
* '''3569'''—Nansur conquers Enathpaneah.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}
* '''3574'''—Nansur conquers the Sacred Lands (Xerash and Amoteu).{{EG|Amoteu}}{{EG|Nansur Empire}}
* '''3588'''—[[Zerxei Triamarius III]], last of the Zerxei Emperors of Nansur, is born.{{EG|Triamarius III}}
* '''3619'''—Zerxei Triamarius III is assassinated by his palace eunuchs at age 31. This marks the end of 108 years of Zerxei rule over Nansur, and the beginning of the [[House Surmante|Surmante]] Emperors.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Surmante, House}}{{EG|Triamarius III}}{{EG|Zerxei, House}} [[Surmante Skilura II]], a future Emperor of Nansur, is born.{{EG|Skilura II}}
* '''3639'''—Surmantic Gates, the great northern gate of Carythusal, are built and financed by [[Surmante Xatantius I]] to commemorate the ill-fated Treaty of [[Kutapileth]], a short-lived military pact between Nansur and High Ainon.{{EG|Surmantic Gates}}<ref group="Notes">This is a '''contradiction.''' According to both ‘Nansur Empire’ and ‘Xatantius I’ Surmante Xatantius I would not be born until 3644. Perhaps 3639 is a mistake for 3693, the year of Xatantius I’s death.</ref>
* '''3644'''—Surmante Xatantius I, Emperor of Nansur is born.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Xatantius I}}
* '''3666'''—[[Pherokar I]], One of [[Kian]]’s earliest and fiercest [[Padirajah]]s, is born.{{EG|Pherokar I}}<ref group="Notes">This date is likely wrong see 3821 below.</ref>
* '''3668'''—The deranged antics Surmante Skilura II “the Mad,” lead to the [[Granary Revolts]]. Skilura II dies at age 49, and Xatantius I takes the throne at age 24.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Skilura II}}{{EG|Xatantius I}}
* '''3669'''—[[Fane]], Prophet of the [[Solitary God]] and founder of [[Fanimry]] is born.{{EG|Fane}}
* '''''c.'' 3683'''—[[Galeoth]] proper begins when King [[Norwain I]] reputedly concluded twenty years of campaigning and conquest by having his captive foes butchered en masse in the reception hall of [[Moraör]], the great palace complex of the Galeoth Kings.{{EG|Galeoth}}
* '''3684'''—In Caraskand, Xatantius raises the fortress [[Insarum]] (later called the Citadel of the Dog).{{EG|Citadel of the Dog}}
* '''3688'''—[[Zarathinius]], famed author of ''[[A Defence of the Arcane Arts]],'' is born.{{EG|Zarathinius}}
* '''3693'''—Surmante Xatantius I dies at age 49, having ruled for 25 years. During his reign, Xatantius I enlarged the Nansur Empire to its greatest extent. He subdued the Norsirai tribes of the Cepalor as far north as the [[River Vindauga]]. For a time he even managed to hold the far southern city of Invishi (though he failed to entirely subdue the Nilnameshi countryside). Despite his military successes, his continual wars exhausted both the Nansur people and the Imperial Treasury and his practice of debasing the talent in order to finance the wars wrecked the empire’s economy. This inadvertently lay the groundwork for the disastrous wars against the Kianene following his death.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Skilura II}}{{EG|Xatantius I}}
* '''3703'''—Fane, a Shrial Priest in the Nansur province of [[Eumarna]], is declared a heretic by the ecclesiastical courts of the Thousand Temples and is banished to certain death in the Carathay Desert. According to Fanim tradition, rather than dying in the desert, Fane went blind, experienced the series of revelations narrated in the ''[[kipfa’aifan]],'' the “Witness of Fane” in Kianni, and was granted miraculous powers (the same powers attributed to the [[Cishaurim]]) he called the Water of Indara. He spent the remainder of his life preaching to and consolidating the desert tribes of the Kianene.{{EG|Fane}}{{EG|''kipfa’aifan''}}
* '''''c.'' 3704'''—The Kianene tribes begin to convert to Fanimry.{{EG|Kian}}
* '''3711'''—[[Hamishaza]], renowned Ainoni dramatist and author of ''[[Tempiras the King]],'' was born.{{EG|Hamishaza}}
* '''3716'''—[[Fan’oukarji I]], the son of the Prophet Fane and the first Padirajah of Kian, is born. Fane was 47 at the birth of his son, and had been living with the Kian for 13 years.{{EG|Fane}}{{EG|Fan’oukarji I}}
* '''3722'''—[[Surmante Caphrianus I]] “the Younger,” Nansur emperor famed for his wily diplomacy and far-reaching reforms of the Nansur legal code, is born.{{EG|Caphrianus I}} The [[Ce Tydonn|Tydonni]] tribes overwhelm the Men of Cengemis at the [[Battle of Marswa]].{{EG|Ce Tydonn}}
* '''3724'''—After living with the Kian for 21 years, Fane managed to convert all the Kianene tribes.{{EG|Kian}}
* '''38th c.'''—Fanic missionaries would succeed in converting the [[Girgash]]i to Fanimry in the thirty-eighth century.{{EG|Kian}}
* '''3739'''—[[Meigeiri]], administrative and spiritual capital of Ce Tydonn, is founded about the Ceneian fortress of [[Meigara]].{{EG|Meigeiri}}
* '''3741'''—King [[Haul-Namyelk]] finally succeeds in unifying the various Tydonni tribes under his absolute authority, Ce Tydonn proper comes into existence.{{EG|Ce Tydonn}}
* '''3742'''—Cengemis is overrun by Tydonni tribes, ending its 370 years of independence. Ce Tydonn is founded in the wake of Cengemis’s collapse.{{EG|Ce Tydonn}}{{EG|Cengemis}} Fane dies at age 73, 39 years after he was banished to the Carathay Desert.{{EG|Fane}}{{EG|''kipfa’aifan''}}
* '''3743'''—At age 27, Fan’oukarji I, first Padirajah of Kian, begins the [[White Jihad]] against the Nansur Empire.{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|White Jihad}}{{EG|Fan’oukarji I}}
* '''3745'''—Zarathinius, author of ''A Defence of the Arcane Arts,'' dies at age 57.{{EG|Zarathinius}}
* '''3752'''—Fan’oukarji I founds [[Nenciphon]] as the administrative capital of Kian, on the banks of the [[River Sweki]].{{EG|Kian}}{{EG|Nenciphon}}
* '''3759'''—[[Mongilea]] becomes original conquest of Fan’oukarji I, it latter be known as the “Green Homeland” of the Kianene.{{EG|Mongilea}}
* '''3771'''—Fan’oukarji I dies at age 55, and after fighting for 28 years, the White Jihad dies with him. In addition to founding Nenciphon and conquering Mongilea, he also made serious inroads into Eumarna.{{EG|Fan’oukarji I}}{{EG|Kian}}{{EG|White Jihad}}
* '''3783'''—Hamishaza, renowned Ainoni dramatist, dies at age 72.{{EG|Hamishaza}}
* '''3785'''—Surmante Caphrianus I “the Younger,” Nansur emperor, dies at age 63.{{EG|Caphrianus I}}
* '''''c.'' 3787'''—As a result of continually pressured by the Sranc tribes that largely ruled the great forests of the [[Dameöri Wilderness]], the [[Thunyerus|Thunyeri]] migrated down the length of the Wernma River. The Thunyeri begin to ply the Three Seas as pirates and raiders, for the next two hundred years.{{EG|Thunyerus}}
* '''3796'''—By order of [[Ekyannus XIV]], the [[Scholastic Wars]] begin. Made up of series of holy wars waged against the Schools, the Scholastic Wars saw the near-destruction of several Schools and the beginning of the Scarlet Spires’ hegemony over High Ainon.{{EG|Scholastic Wars}}
* '''3801'''—During the height of the Scholastic Wars, Grandmaster [[Shinurta]] of the Scarlet Spires creates the [[Javreh]] slave-soldiers.{{EG|Javreh}} Kian captures Eumarna from Nansur during a Jihad.{{EG|Kian}}
* '''3804'''—To defend themselves during the Scholastic Wars, the [[Mikka Council]] from Cironji, the [[Oaranat]] from Nilnamesh, and the (Cengemic) [[Nilitar Compact]] from Ce Tydonn join together to form the [[Mysunsai]] “mercenary School.” During the War under the terms of the infamous Psailian Concession, the Mysunsai assisted the Inrithi in their Ainoni campaigns.{{EG|Mysunsai}}
* '''3808'''—[[Sorainas]], celebrated Nansur scriptural commentator, and author of ''[[The Book of Circles and Spirals]],'' is born.{{EG|Sorainas}}
* '''3817'''—[[House Morghund]] becomes the ruling dynasty of Atrithau.{{EG|Morghund, House}}
* '''3818'''—After 22 years, the Scholastic Wars come to an end. By this time, the School of the Scarlet Spires, based in Carythusal, managed to destroy the army of King [[Horziah III]] and assumed indirect control of High Ainon.{{EG|High Ainon}}{{EG|Scholastic Wars}}
* '''3821'''—Pherokar I, one of Kian’s earliest and fiercest Padirajahs, dies at age 155.{{EG|Pherokar I}}<ref group="Notes">This extremely long life is likely an '''error.''' Only three other people are said to have lived over 100 (Anasûrimbor Nanor-Ukkerja at 178 in 1556; Ajencis at 103 in 2000; and Triamis the Great at 121 in 2577) and only Nanor-Ukkerja lived longer than 155. Also the earliest he could have started his reign is after Fan’oukarji I’s death in 3771. Pherokar I would have already been 105 at the time. Perhaps his true date of birth should then be 3766, if so he would have been too young to be Padirajah directly after Fan’oukarji I, but could have been a latter ruler, perhaps during 3801 to lead the conquest of Eumarna at age 35, and then dying at 55.</ref>
* '''3823'''—[[Nersei Onoyas II]], King of Conriya who first forged the alliance between the School of Mandate and [[House Nersei]], is born.{{EG|Onoyas II, Nersei}}
* '''3839'''—Caraskand, and its fortress Insarum (later called the Citadel of the Dog), are captured by the Fanim. They rename the fortress Il’huda, “the Bulwark” in Kianni.{{EG|Citadel of the Dog}}
* '''3842'''—Kian captures Enathpaneah in a Jihad.{{EG|Kian}}
* '''3845'''—Kian captures both Xerash and Amoteu. The [[College of Marucee]], a College of the Thousand Temples is destroyed in the Sack of Shimeh.{{EG|Amoteu}}{{EG|Kian}}
* '''3878'''—Nersei Onoyas II, King of Conriya who first forged the alliance between the School of Mandate and House Nersei, dies at age 55.{{EG|Onoyas II, Nersei}}
* '''3892'''—[[Habal ab Sarouk]], first organizes the [[Coyauri]], the famed elite heavy cavalry of the Kianene Padirajah, as a response to the Nansur [[Kidruhil]].{{EG|Coyauri}}
* '''3895'''—Sorainas, celebrated Nansur scriptural commentator, and author of ''The Book of Circles and Spirals,'' dies at age 87.{{EG|Sorainas}}
* '''3905'''—[[Anwurat]], a large Kianene fortress to the south of the [[River Sempis] Delta is built.{{EG|Anwurat}}
* '''3921'''—The School of Mandate give the tower Attrempus to be held in trust by House Nersei of Conriya.{{EG|Attrempus}}
* '''3933'''—The Kian conquer both Shigek and [[Gedea]] during the [[Dagger Jihad]] of [[Fan’oukarji III]].{{EG|Kian}}{{EG|Shigek}}{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Ikurei Dynasty}} The [[College of Sareöt]], a College of the Thousand Temples dedicated to the preservation of knowledge, was destroyed during the fall of Shigek. However, their library, the [[Sareötic Library]], was spared by Fan’oukarji III, thinking it the will of the Solitary God.{{EG|College of Sareöt}}{{EG|Sareotic Library}} After the fall of Shigek, the Nansur built a number of small fortresses in the Gedean interior, including [[Dayrut]], [[Ebara]] and [[Kurrut]].{{EG|Dayrut}}{{EG|Ebara}}{{EG|Kurrut}}
* '''3941'''—Following a coup brought about by the turmoil following the loss of Shigek to the Kianene, the Surmante Emperors lose control of the Nansur after 322 years. A former Exalt-General, [[Ikurei Sorius I]] reorganized both the Imperial Army and the empire, becoming the first [[House Ikurei|Ikurei]] emperor. These changes allowed him and his descendants to defeat no fewer than three full-scale Fanim invasions.{{EG|Ikurei Dynasty}}{{EG|Ikurei, House}}{{EG|Nansur Empire}}{{EG|Surmante, House}}
* '''3942'''—The entire line of King [[Nejata Medekki]] of Conriya is murdered during the Aöknyssian Uprisings. House Nersei becomes the ruling House of Conriya.{{EG|Nersei, House}}<ref group="Notes">This is a '''contradiction.''' Onoyas II, Nersei is said to be king before his death in 3878, but here the Nersei only become kings in 3942. Additionally, Attrempus is turned over to House Nersei in 3921, presumably they were already kings at this point. If the year of the Aöknyssian Uprisings was in fact 3842, then Nersei Onoyas II would have been the first Nersei king at age 19.</ref>
* '''3987'''—After three generations of Inrithi missionaries had largely converted the Thunyeri from their traditional Kiünnat beliefs, the tribes elected their first King, [[Hringa Hurrausch]], and began adopting the institutions of their Three Seas neighbours.{{EG|Thunyerus}}
* '''4000'''—By the end of the fourth millennium Kian was easily the pre-eminent military and commercial power of the Three Seas, and a source of endless consternation not only for the much-diminished Nansur Empire but for Inrithi Princes in every nation.{{EG|Kian}} [[Haurut urs Mab]], an [[Utemot]] memorialist when [[Cnaiür urs Skiötha]] was a child, is born.{{EG|Haurut urs Mab}}
