[[File:Mog redux.jpg|thumb|300px|Mog-Pharau, the No-God, in his dread Carapace, attended by members of the Consult.]]
The '''No-God''' is an entity summoned by the [[Consult]] in the spring of the year 2143 to bring about the [[Apocalypse]], and again in 4132 during the [[Second Apocalypse]].
Very little is known about the No-God, save that he utterly lacks remorse or compassion and possesses terrible power, including the ability to control [[Sranc]], [[Bashrag]], and [[Wracu]] as extensions of his own will. Because of his armor, the so-called Carapace, which eyewitnesses describe as an iron (or [[nimil]]{{2|7}}) sarcophagus suspended in the heart of a mountainous whirlwind, it is not even known whether he is a creature of flesh or of spirit. According to [[Mandate]] scholars, the [[Inchoroi]] worship him as their savior, as do — according to some — the [[Scylvendi]].{{EG|No-God}}
Somehow, his mere existence is antithetical to human life: during the entirety of the Apocalypse, not one infant drew breath — all were stillborn. He is apparently immune to [[sorcery]] (according to legend, eleven [[Chorae]] are embedded in the Carapace). The [[Heron Spear]] is the only known weapon that can harm him.{{EG|No-God}}
The No-God was killed by [[Anaxophus V]] at the [[Second Battle of Mengedda]] in 2155.{{EG|Battle of Mengedda, the Second}} According to popular legend, his body turned to ash, which swept across the land and caused the [[Indigo Plague]]. Mandate scholars dispute this, claiming that the No-God’s body was recovered by the Consult and interred in [[Golgotterath]].{{EG|Indigo Plague}} Whatever the outcome, the No-God was summoned once more before Golgotterath in 4132.
=== ''The Unholy Consult'' === During the final moments of the battle for Golgotterath, the No-God was summoned. Once again, all across the world, humans could feel his presence. Babies were again stillborn. His resurrection caused the [[Great Ordeal]] to scatter in panic, therefore beginning the Second Apocalypse. The Hordes swarmed around him, and the remaining armies of [[Anasûrimbor Kellhus]] were destroyed. <ref>''The Unholy Consult, ''Chapter 20</ref>
==Other Names== Known as Mog-Pharau (from which “No-God” is derived{{2|1}}) in ancient [[Kûniüri]]c. Known as Tsurumah (“Hated One”{{EG|Tsurumah}}) in ancient [[Kyranean]]. Known as Lokung (“Dead-God”{{EG|Lokung}}) to the [[Scylvendi]]. Known as Mursiris (“Wicked North”{{EG|Mursiris}}) to the [[Shiradi Empire|Shiradi]]. Known as Cara-Sincurimoi (“Angel of Endless Hunger”{{EG|Cara-Sincurimoi}}) by the [[Nonmen]]. Known as Great Ruiner to the surviving tribes of [[Men]] in the [[Ancient North]].{{EG|Great Ruiner}} Known as World-Breaker.{{EG|World-Breaker}}
== Nature == No-God is invisible from the outside, therefore the Gods cannot see him and help their believers against him.
Author explained in Q/A: ''A better way to think of the No-God is as a philosophical zombie (p-zombie), of a piece with all the other soulless instruments of the Inchoroi. A perfectly unconscious god, and so in that respect, entirely at one with material reality, continuous with it, and so an agency invisible to the Outside.''
==References== <references/> [[Category:Gods]]

[[File:Ark-of-the-Skies.jpg|thumb|300px|Concept sketch of the Inchoroi Ark-of-the-Skies.]] [[File:Ark sm.jpg|thumb|300px|The Ark of the Inchoroi topples from the void …]] The '''Incû-Holoinas''' (“Ark-of-the-Skies” in [[Languages|Ihrimsû]]) is the great space-faring vessel that brought the [[Inchoroi]] from the void and became the golden heart of [[Golgotterath]]. The Ark's most famed feature are the two massive Golden Horns - or the "Oars of the Ark" - that protrude above the ground. It is assumed that the Horns were located at the rear of the vessel when it was in flight.{{EG|Incû-Holoinas}} The Ark's crash-landing, in the event known as [[Arkfall]] was violent enough to damage one of the two horns, leaving one upright and the other slightly canted.<ref>''[[The Unholy Consult]]''</ref>
{{Blockquote|A cavernous void opened before them. It reminded Seswatha of a ship’s ribbed hold, though pitched on its end, and far too vast to truly resemble any work of Men. Sheer golden faces reared into obscurity, hazed by the smoke of countless fires. Structures of mortise and hacked stone climbed their foundations, crusting their sides like stacked hornets’ nests, not dwellings but open cells, squalid and innumerable.|The Ark’s interior as witnessed by [[Seswatha]]{{3|14}}}}
Some speculate that the Ark itself once lived; the Inchoroi call themselves “Children of the Ark” and the most ancient [[Nonmen]] songs refer to them as “the Orphans.”{{3|12}}
==Size== The size of the Ark is heavily disputed by scholars, even in [[Far Antiquity]], with accounts varying tremendously.
According to one source, the Ark in totality is three thousand cubits in length, five hundred in width, and three hundred in depth.<ref>''[[The Thousandfold Thought]]''</ref> However, ancient [[Nonman]] records and the ''[[Isûphiryas]]'' place the size of the Upright Horn alone at over ten thousand Nonman cubits in length. [[Sohonc]] measurements, rooted in mathematics and the measurement of the Horn's shadow, give an allegedly far more accurate reading of 9,724 Umeritic cubits in length.<ref>Encyclopedic Glossary II, 'Incû-Holoinas'</ref> This suggests that the Upright Horn alone may exceed 13,700 feet (or 2.6 miles) in height. The Nonman measurements would be double this.
